			<p>To answer your initial question: Yes, unions can exist in a world void of aggression and theft.</p>
<p>The fortunate thing about a free market society without government enforced license requirements and such things is that the number of electricians and in fact all professionals, the prices they charge, etc. will not simply stay within your arbitrarily made up confines, but rather continuously fluctuate and adapt to market demand so as to smoothen out the possibility of radical events like the one you described above.</p>
<p>I would point out though, that in a statist society such events occur a lot and escalate all too often to the point where there&#8217;s blood in the streets, so I find it kind of funny that you would advance it as an argument against anti-statism.</p>
