			December 26th, 2012 12:01 am             </div>
            
			<div class="commenttext">
			<p>&#8220;Private land ownership is control over land acquired by either homesteading unused land or by taking over control of used land from someone else without aggression.&#8221;</p>
<p>No. Homesteading (if you bother to read Locke and even subsequent to that, Nozick) is insufficient. Homesteading requires *compensation* for the expropriation (i.e., site-rents), because &#8220;as much and as good&#8221; must be left in common.</p>
<p>And even if this wasn&#8217;t the case, history makes it abundantly clear that land ownership is the result of violence. Or do voluntaryists merely believe in cementing the results of such aggression into permanence?</p>
<p>I know! Once I establish a mighty slave-state *then* I&#8217;ll declare myself a voluntaryist! That way I can say I&#8217;m against violence *and* receive the benefits from it.</p>
			</div>

		</li>

	
	
		<li>
		    <div class="commenttitle">
		    <img alt='' src='http://www.gravatar.com/avatar/9dcace9b2cce7316bd46e6e9f83d892c?s=40&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D40&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-40 photo' height='40' width='40' />	
			<a href='http://www.economicsjunkie.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Nima</a>			 on
			December 26th, 2012 4:54 am             </div>
            
			<div class="commenttext">
			<blockquote><p>“Private land ownership is control over land acquired by either homesteading unused land or by taking over control of used land from someone else without aggression.”</p>
<p>No. Homesteading (if you bother to read Locke and even subsequent to that, Nozick) is insufficient. Homesteading requires *compensation* for the expropriation (i.e., site-rents), because “as much and as good” must be left in common.</p></blockquote>
<p>Fortunately it&#8217;s not an argument to simply say &#8220;No.&#8221; to a definition or drop names of authors you have read. When I say private ownership I mean precisely what I said above.</p>
<blockquote><p>And even if this wasn’t the case, history makes it abundantly clear that land ownership is the result of violence.</p></blockquote>
<p>Yes, that is a pretty obvious and not necessarily earth shattering tidbit of historical fact. The good news I have for you: I&#8217;m not aware that I have ever stated anything to the contrary, so it would seem to me like you&#8217;re running into open doors on this one, if that makes sense?</p>
<blockquote><p>Or do voluntaryists merely believe in cementing the results of such aggression into permanence?</p>
<p>Just in case you were genuinely looking for an answer: No.</p>
<blockquote><p>I know! Once I establish a mighty slave-state *then* I’ll declare myself a voluntaryist! That way I can say I’m against violence *and* receive the benefits from it.</p></blockquote>
<p>Ugh, come on man, grow up, will ya?! :D</p></blockquote>
			</div>

		</li>

	
	
		<li>
		    <div class="commenttitle">
		    <img alt='' src='http://www.gravatar.com/avatar/75ce8f8153f126479e1cc74e2d6abf20?s=40&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D40&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-40 photo' height='40' width='40' />	
			<a href='http://isocracy.org' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Lev Lafayette</a>			 on
			December 26th, 2012 7:13 pm             </div>
            
			<div class="commenttext">
			<p>&#8220;When I say private ownership I mean precisely what I said above.&#8221;</p>
<p>Right, voluntaryists support the unjust appropriation of natural resources from the community in perpetuity. Landlord monopolists who, laughably, make a claim to be &#8216;anarchists&#8217;.  </p>
<p>We also understand that voluntaryists support existing property rights as long as they are formed by &#8220;free contract&#8221;.  Well guess what? Not all contracts are equal. A voluntary agreement does not mean an agreement by free and informed consent. </p>
<p>Free given wage contracts! The ignorance of the voluntaryist to class relations (ohh, scary words) to the person who has nothing but their labour to &#8220;voluntarily&#8221; offer or &#8220;voluntarily&#8221; suffer deprivations, is obviously equal to the &#8220;voluntary&#8221; offer of the employer.</p>
<p>For a site entitled &#8220;economics junkie&#8221; the author could do well to look labour market monopsony. They might learn something.</p>
			</div>

		</li>

	
	
		<li>
		    <div class="commenttitle">
		    <img alt='' src='http://www.gravatar.com/avatar/9dcace9b2cce7316bd46e6e9f83d892c?s=40&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D40&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-40 photo' height='40' width='40' />	
			<a href='http://www.economicsjunkie.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Nima</a>			 on
			December 27th, 2012 5:27 pm             </div>
            
			<div class="commenttext">
			<blockquote><p>Right, voluntaryists support the unjust appropriation of natural resources from the community in perpetuity. Landlord monopolists who, laughably, make a claim to be ‘anarchists’.</p></blockquote>
<p>Actually no, but nice try putting words in my mouth.</p>
<blockquote><p>We also understand that voluntaryists support existing property rights as long as they are formed by “free contract”. Well guess what? Not all contracts are equal. A voluntary agreement does not mean an agreement by free and informed consent.</p></blockquote>
<p>Voluntaryism says that nobody shall be permitted to initiate the occupation of another&#8217;s body or property. I never said all contracts are equal, and I&#8217;m not sure if anybody would make such a stupid statement. Voluntary agreement means an agreement without use or threat of aggression. I hope that helps.</p>
<blockquote><p>Free given wage contracts! The ignorance of the voluntaryist to class relations (ohh, scary words) to the person who has nothing but their labour to “voluntarily” offer or “voluntarily” suffer deprivations, is obviously equal to the “voluntary” offer of the employer.</p></blockquote>
<p>I don&#8217;t know that I ever stated that there&#8217;s nothing unpleasant about doing physical labor, or any labor for that matter. Now I will say that the existence of capital on the market which is made available by its owners allows the worker to increase the output of his (otherwise manual) labor and thus helps lift his real wages, since workers also make up the bulk of consumption on the market place.</p>
<blockquote><p>For a site entitled “economics junkie” the author could do well to look labour market monopsony. They might learn something.</p></blockquote>
<p>Yes I&#8217;m familiar with that concept, and I have pointed out many times that in a peaceful dynamic market, without government licensure, monopoly protection, labor unions, minimum wage laws etc., in other words without aggression wherever you look, the phenomenon would be completely irrelevant because non existent.</p>
			</div>

		</li>

	
	
		<li>
		    <div class="commenttitle">
		    <img alt='' src='http://www.gravatar.com/avatar/75ce8f8153f126479e1cc74e2d6abf20?s=40&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D40&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-40 photo' height='40' width='40' />	
			<a href='http://isocracy.org' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Lev Lafayette</a>			 on
			December 27th, 2012 7:30 pm             </div>
            
			<div class="commenttext">
			<p>&#8220;Actually no, but nice try putting words in my mouth.&#8221;</p>
<p>I&#8217;m not. You have already stated you support homesteading in perpetuity. That&#8217;s landlordism. So is accepting voluntary purchase and sale of land that has originally been acquired through violence. </p>
<p>Further the violent protection of such property rights to exclude others *is* the very definition of the state. The claim that voluntaryists are anarchists is nonsense. You can&#8217;t have anarchism which recognises property rights, because property rights require a State.</p>
<p>&#8220;I never said all contracts are equal, and I’m not sure if anybody would make such a stupid statement. Voluntary agreement means an agreement without use or threat of aggression.&#8221;</p>
<p>But even the best contracts are made with the threats of circumstance, and some are worse than others. There is no such thing as an ideal speech situation, it&#8217;s an ideal. The fairest contract is one created in the circumstances where parties have the highest possible level of free choice, both through positive and negative freedoms.</p>
<p>&#8220;Yes I’m familiar with that concept, and I have pointed out many times that in a peaceful dynamic market, without government licensure, monopoly protection, labor unions, minimum wage laws etc., in other words without aggression wherever you look, the phenomenon would be completely irrelevant because non existent.&#8221;</p>
<p>You don&#8217;t understand the concept. It is *impossible* in any &#8220;peaceful dynamic&#8221; market where there is an imbalance between purchasers of labour and the sellers of labour for a fair price to arise. That is why minimum wages ^ etc are implemented to redress that balance. </p>
<p>*Most* markets in their &#8220;free&#8221; state are in fact, imperfect and unfair due to an imbalance in property relations. They are not  free and consensual, even if they have the illusion of being voluntary.</p>
<p>But nice to see you want to abolish unions. Voluntarily, I am sure.</p>
			</div>

		</li>

	
	
		<li>
		    <div class="commenttitle">
		    <img alt='' src='http://www.gravatar.com/avatar/9dcace9b2cce7316bd46e6e9f83d892c?s=40&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D40&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-40 photo' height='40' width='40' />	
			<a href='http://www.economicsjunkie.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Nima</a>			 on
			December 27th, 2012 9:12 pm             </div>
            
			<div class="commenttext">
			<blockquote><p>“Actually no, but nice try putting words in my mouth.”</p>
<p>I’m not. You have already stated you support homesteading in perpetuity. That’s landlordism. So is accepting voluntary purchase and sale of land that has originally been acquired through violence.</p></blockquote>
<p>Wow, that&#8217;s truly amazing. You say you&#8217;re not putting words in my mouth and in the same paragraph you make up even more things that I never said. I support everyone&#8217;s right to defend his body and property that he acquired without aggression. That&#8217;s all. Is it really that hard for you to attack my position without morphing it into something else every time you try?</p>
<blockquote><p>Further the violent protection of such property rights to exclude others *is* the very definition of the state. The claim that voluntaryists are anarchists is nonsense. You can’t have anarchism which recognises property rights, because property rights require a State.</p></blockquote>
<p>See, therein lies your problem. If you don&#8217;t know the definitions of the terms I&#8217;m using you&#8217;re not going to get anywhere. If you genuinely think that the state is by definition a protector of property rights, then everything you&#8217;re saying there makes perfect sense, in the same sense that if I redefine 2=3 and then say 2+2=6. I mean, it&#8217;s completely deranged and embarrassing to see you do this, but it &#8220;makes sense&#8221; if those are your premises.</p>
<blockquote><p>But even the best contracts are made with the threats of circumstance, and some are worse than others. There is no such thing as an ideal speech situation, it’s an ideal. The fairest contract is one created in the circumstances where parties have the highest possible level of free choice, both through positive and negative freedoms.</p></blockquote>
<p>OK, but I&#8217;m not sure how that is a response to me saying &#8220;Voluntary agreement means an agreement without use or threat of aggression.&#8221; Are you generally able to stay on target in conversations or do you often find yourself drifting like this?</p>
<blockquote><p>You don’t understand the concept. It is *impossible* in any “peaceful dynamic” market where there is an imbalance between purchasers of labour and the sellers of labour for a fair price to arise. That is why minimum wages ^ etc are implemented to redress that balance.</p></blockquote>
<p>I don&#8217;t know if you&#8217;ve ever been an entrepreneur, had to deal with customers, hire workers etc, or if you&#8217;re familiar with one of the least government infested industries, the IT industry, and what&#8217;s going on our there in the world with solutions such as odesk, guru, elance etc. but what you&#8217;re saying strongly indicates that you genuinely don&#8217;t now how market dynamics in a peaceful market work and feel in a visceral sense (and there&#8217;s nothing wrong with that if that&#8217;s the case, I&#8217;m just pointing it out). In any case: There is no such thing as a fair price, the employer of course always wants it to be as low as possible, and the employee wants it to be as high as possible. It is in the peaceful market where these imbalances are reconciled and where both sides come to peaceful agreements; where peaceful doesn&#8217;t always mean ungrudging or perfect by any means of course, I can tell from experience :)</p>
<p>I hope that helps.</p>
			</div>

		</li>

	
	
		<li>
		    <div class="commenttitle">
		    <img alt='' src='http://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6c66f2e601527a83c01119dabc1bda44?s=40&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D40&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-40 photo' height='40' width='40' />	
			John			 on
			June 9th, 2013 8:28 am             </div>
            
			<div class="commenttext">
			<p>&#8220;OK, so we know that private individuals and corporations were willing to give $307.65 billion to charitable organizations on a completely voluntary basis.</p>
<p>How much of this money actually ends up in the hands of the needy? According to reputable charitable auditing and rating websites, such as Razoo this number seems to be around 80-85% on average.</p>
<p>So around $246 billion ended up in the hands of poor people as a result of completely voluntary charity donations in the US.&#8221;</p>
<p>Isn&#8217;t this analysis deeply flawed? It assumes that all charitable donations go to charities delivering direct services to the poor &#8212; when in fact it includes donations to legal nonprofits, animal shelters, troop-supporting yellow ribbon efforts, etc. </p>
<p>A more effective analysis would delineate how much of that sum goes directly to charities providing direct client services or relief to low-income populations.</p>
			</div>

		</li>

	
	
