		<li>
		    <div class="commenttitle">
		    <img alt='' src='http://www.gravatar.com/avatar/504161d0257c0b4d4336868bd7904b7c?s=40&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D40&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-40 photo' height='40' width='40' />	
			<a href='http://nickschannel.github.io' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Nick Econopouly</a>			 on
			May 25th, 2014 5:51 am             </div>
            
			<div class="commenttext">
			<p>I would have to agree that your analysis of charity in the US seems flawed a bit&#8230; not that it matters. Because governments create poor people and farm off of them.<br />
One thing I&#8217;d like to add is that some of the problems mentioned in the comments would have solutions found in social change as well. As an anarcho-capitalist (as far as I can tell), you tend to talk only about anti-statist problems and solutions found in Voluntaryism. But a transition to a free society would not ONLY be political, and economic. There would have to be a widespread social acceptance of voluntaryism, and I think that movement would also involve social changes such as more home gardening. I think that people exposed to these social changes would not find themselves at risk from the typical statist worries: That without regulation companies would turn into massive, evil monopolies. Of course what YOU would argue is that a true free market would never allow that to happen&#8230; But I think that socially aware voluntaryists would have no problem going beyond boycotting and nonviolent approaches. I think, for instance, that if a fracking company began to interrupt the environment enough to hurt nearby communities, they would readily use violence (or the threat of violence), as well as the expected activism, internet broadcasts, etc. to stop the company. As opposed to the free market magically working it out. What if the customers of the fracking company were from far away? Their demand would not be what kept the company in check.</p>
			</div>

		</li>

	
	
